se into the long, difficult, but ultimately rewarding effort to successfully conclude negotiations between a National Football League (NFL) franchise, the NFL, and a multitude of players from the political arena, including Governor Andrew Cuomo and US Senator Chuck Schumer. Poloncarz discusses the financial side of sports and reveals how the county was able to navigate what proved to be often-turbulent waters. Complicating negotiations was an ongoing frenzy in the local news media, hungry for any news about the new lease, and Bills team owner Ralph C. Wilson Jr., who was ninety-two and had said the team would be sold upon his death, thereby possibly being relocated to another city. In the end, a new lease was signed and the Bills remained in Buffalo at a time when a number of similar sized communities watched their teams relocate to other cities in larger markets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFootball stadiumszNew York (State)zBuffaloxHistory. 0aFootballxEconomic aspectszNew York (State)zBuffalo. 0aSports and statezNew York (State)zBuffalo. 4aBusiness and Economics : Business and Government. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : State and Local Politics. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Sports and Society. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Football.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847595040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438475950423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438475950/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles